<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Complex Numbers</h1>=20


<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
omplex-example.svg" alt=3D"complex example 7 + 3i" height=3D"58" width=3D"1=
57"> <i><br>
A Complex Number</i></p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center">A Complex Number is a combination of a<br>
<b>Real Number</b> and an <b>Imaginary Number</b></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"words">=20
<p class=3D"large"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/real-numbe=
rs.html">Real Numbers</a> are numbers like:</p>=20

<div class=3D"simple center large">
	<div class=3D"box">1</div>
	<div class=3D"box">12,38</div>
	<div class=3D"box">=E2=88=920,8625</div>
	<div class=3D"box">3/4</div>
	<div class=3D"box">=E2=88=9A2</div>
	<div class=3D"box">1998</div>
</div>=20

<p>Nearly any number you can think of is a Real Number!</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p class=3D"large"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/imaginary-=
numbers.html">Imaginary Numbers</a> when <b>squared</b> give a <b>negative<=
/b> result.</p>=20
<p>Normally this doesn't happen, because:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>when we <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/square-root.html">square=
</a> a positive number we get a positive result, and</li>=20
	<li>when we square a negative number we also get a positive result (becaus=
e <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/multiplying-negatives.html">a negat=
ive times a negative gives a positive</a>), for example <b>=E2=88=922 =C3=
=97 =E2=88=922 <em>=3D</em> +4</b></li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>But just imagine such numbers exist, because we want them.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Let's talk some more about imaginary numbers ...</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p>The "unit" imaginary number (like <span class=3D"large">1</span> for Rea=
l Numbers) is <span class=3D"large">i</span>, which is the square root of =
=E2=88=921</p>=20
<div class=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/image=
s/imaginary-square-root.svg" alt=3D"equals the square root of -1" height=3D=
"44" width=3D"135"></div>

<p>When we square <span class=3D"large">i</span> we get <span class=3D"larg=
e">=E2=88=921</span></p>=20
<p class=3D"larger center">i<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=921</p>=20
<p>Examples of Imaginary Numbers:</p>=20


<div class=3D"simple center large">
<div class=3D"box">3i</div>
<div class=3D"box">1,04i</div>
<div class=3D"box">=E2=88=922,8i</div>
<div class=3D"box">3i/4</div>
<div class=3D"box">(=E2=88=9A2)i</div>
<div class=3D"box">1998i</div>

</div>=20
=20

<p>And we keep that little "i" there to remind us we still need to multiply=
 by =E2=88=9A=E2=88=921</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Complex Numbers</h2>=20

<p>When we combine a Real Number and an Imaginary Number we get a <b>Comple=
x Number</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
omplex-number.svg" alt=3D"Complex Number" height=3D"80" width=3D"290"></p>=
=20

<h3>Examples:</h3>=20


<div class=3D"simple center large">
<div class=3D"box">1 + i</div>
<div class=3D"box">39 + 3i</div>
<div class=3D"box">0,8 =E2=88=92 2,2i</div>
<div class=3D"box">&gt;=E2=88=922 + <span class=3D"times">=CF=80</span>i&lt=
;</div>
<div class=3D"box">=E2=88=9A2 + i/2</div>
</div>

<div class=3D"gap"></div>=20

<div class=3D"center80">=20

<h3>Can a Number be a Combination of Two Numbers?</h3>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/fraction=
s/pizza-3-8.svg" alt=3D"pie 3/8" height=3D"120" width=3D"120"></p>=20
<p>Can we make a number from two other numbers? Sure we can!</p>=20
<p>We do it with <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/fractions.html">frac=
tions</a> all the time. The fraction <span class=3D"frac-large"><sup>3</sup=
>/<sub>8</sub></span> is a number made up of a 3 and an 8. We know it means=
 "3 of 8 equal parts".</p>=20
<p>Well, a Complex Number is just <b>two numbers added together</b> (a Real=
 and an Imaginary Number).</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Either Part Can Be Zero</h2>=20

<p>So, a Complex Number has a real part and an imaginary part.</p>=20
<p>But either part can be <b>0</b>, so <span class=3D"large">all Real Numbe=
rs and Imaginary Numbers are also Complex Numbers</span>.</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th style=3D"width: 120px;" scope=3D"col">Complex Number</th>
			<th style=3D"width: 120px;" scope=3D"col">Real Part</th>
			<th style=3D"width: 120px;" scope=3D"col">Imaginary Part</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">&nbsp;</th>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">3 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span></td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">3</td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">2</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">5</td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">5</td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;"><b>0</b></td>
			<td>Purely Real</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">=E2=88=926i</td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;"><b>0</b></td>
			<td style=3D"width:120px;">=E2=88=926</td>
			<td>Purely Imaginary</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Complicated?</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/=
building-complex.jpg" alt=3D"building complex" height=3D"151" width=3D"150"=
></p>=20
<p>Complex does <b>not</b> mean complicated.</p>=20
<p>It means the two types of numbers, real and imaginary, together form a <=
b>complex</b>, just like a building complex (buildings joined together).</p=
>=20
</div>=20


<h2>A Visual Explanation</h2>=20

<p>You know how the number line goes <b>left-right</b>?</p>=20
<p>Well let's have the imaginary numbers go <b>up-down</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/c=
omplex-plane.svg" alt=3D"complex plane" height=3D"250" width=3D"250"><br>
<br>
And we get the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/complex-plane.=
html">Complex Plane</a></p>=20
<p>A complex number can now be shown as a point:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/c=
omplex-plane-3-4i.svg" alt=3D"complex plane 3+4i" height=3D"332" width=3D"3=
32"><br>
The complex number 3 + 4<b>i</b></p>=20


<h2>Properties</h2>=20

<p>The letter <b>z</b> is often used for a complex number:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large larger">z <em>=3D</em> a + bi</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>z</b> is a Complex Number</li>=20
	<li><b>a</b> and <b>b</b> are <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/number=
s/real-numbers.html">Real Numbers</a></li>=20
	<li><b>i</b> is the unit imaginary number <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A=E2=88=921=
</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>we refer to the real part and imaginary part using <b>Re</b> and <b>Im</=
b> like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">Re(z) <em>=3D</em> a<br>
Im(z) <em>=3D</em> b</p>=20
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/conjugate.html">conjug=
ate</a> (it changes the sign in the middle) of <b>z</b> is shown with a sta=
r:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">z<sup>*</sup> <em>=3D</em> a =E2=88=92 bi</p>=20
<p>We can also use angle and distance like this (called <b>polar form</b>):=
</p>=20
<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images=
/complex-plane-3-4i-polar.svg" alt=3D"complex plane 3-4i is polar 5 at 0.92=
7" height=3D"332" width=3D"332"></div>

<p>So the complex number <b>3 + 4i</b> can also be shown as <b>distance 5</=
b> and <b>angle 0,927 radians</b>. To convert from one form to the other us=
e <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/polar-cartesian-coordinates.html">C=
artesian to Polar conversion</a>.</p>=20
<p>The magnitude of <b>z</b> is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">|z| <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9A(a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup=
>2</sup>)</p>=20
<p>And the angle of <b>z</b>, also called <b>Arg(z)</b> is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">Arg(z) <em>=3D</em> tan<sup>-1</=
sup>(b/a)</span><br>
(for a&gt;0)</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <b>z <em>=3D</em> 3 + 4i</b></h3>=20

	<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/imag=
es/complex-plane-arg.svg" alt=3D"complex plane with z=3D3+4i" height=3D"297=
" width=3D"297"></div>

<ul class=3D"disc">=20
	<li><b>z</b> is a Complex Number</li>=20
	<li>3 and 4 are Real Numbers</li>=20
	<li>Re(z) <em>=3D</em> 3</li>=20
	<li>Im(z) <em>=3D</em> 4</li>=20
	<li>|z|&nbsp;=3D =E2=88=9A(3<sup>2</sup> + 4<sup>2</sup>) <em>=3D</em> 5</=
li>=20
	<li>Arg(z) <em>=3D</em> tan<sup>-1</sup>(4/3) <em>=3D</em> 0,927... radian=
s</li>=20
	<li>z<sup>*</sup> <em>=3D</em> 3 =E2=88=92 4i</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Adding</h2>=20

<p>To add two complex numbers we add each part separately:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">(a+b<b>i</b>) + (c+d<b>i</b>) <em>=3D</em> (a+c)=
 + (b+d)<b>i</b></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: add the complex numbers <b>3 + 2<i>i</i></b> and <b>1 + 7<i>i=
</i></b></h3>=20

	<ul class=3D"dart">=20
		<li>add the real numbers, and</li>=20
		<li>add the imaginary numbers:</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p class=3D"center">(3 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span>) + (1 + 7<span cl=
ass=3D"large">i</span>)<br>
=3D 3 + 1 + (2 + 7)<i><b>i</b></i><br>
=3D 4 + 9<span class=3D"large">i</span></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Let's try another:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: add the complex numbers <b>3 + 5<i>i</i></b> and <b>4 =E2=88=
=92 3<i>i</i></b></h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center">(3 + 5<i><b>i</b></i>) + (4 =E2=88=92 3<i><b>i</b></i>=
)<br>
=3D 3 + 4 + (5 =E2=88=92 3)<i><b>i</b></i><br>
=3D 7 + 2<i><b>i</b></i></p>=20
	<p>On the complex plane it is:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
complex-plane-vector-add.svg" alt=3D"complex plane vector addition" height=
=3D"187" width=3D"236"></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Multiplying</h2>=20

<p>To multiply complex numbers:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><b>Each part of the first complex number</b> gets multi=
plied by<br>
<b>each part of the second complex number</b></p>=20
<p>Just use "FOIL", which stands for "<b>F</b>irsts, <b>O</b>uters, <b>I</b=
>nners, <b>L</b>asts" (see <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/po=
lynomials-multiplying.html">Binomial Multiplication</a> for more details):<=
/p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td> <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/foil-complex.=
svg" alt=3D"foil" height=3D"133" width=3D"238"></td>
			<td>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Firsts: <b>a =C3=97 c</b></li>=20
	<li>Outers: <b>a =C3=97 d<i>i</i></b></li>=20
	<li>Inners: <b>b<i>i</i> =C3=97 c</b></li>=20
	<li>Lasts: <b>b<i>i</i> =C3=97 d<i>i</i></b></li>=20
</ul></td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td colspan=3D"2">=20
<p class=3D"larger">(a+b<i><b>i</b></i>)(c+d<i><b>i</b></i>) <em>=3D</em> a=
c + ad<b><i>i</i></b> + bc<b><i>i</i></b> + bd<b><i>i</i><sup>2</sup></b></=
p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: (3 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span>)(1 + 7<span class=3D"lar=
ge">i</span>)</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"two">  <span class=3D"lt">(3 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</spa=
n>)(1 + 7<span class=3D"large">i</span>) </span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D 3=
=C3=971 + 3=C3=977<span class=3D"large">i</span> + 2<span class=3D"large">i=
</span>=C3=971+ 2<span class=3D"large">i</span>=C3=977<span class=3D"large"=
>i</span></span> <span class=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D 3 + 21<s=
pan class=3D"large">i</span> + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span> + 14<span cl=
ass=3D"large">i</span><sup>2</sup></span> <span class=3D"lt"></span>=20
		<span class=3D"rt">=3D 3 + 21<span class=3D"large">i</span> + 2<span clas=
s=3D"large">i</span> =E2=88=92 14</span>=20
	=09
		<p>&nbsp; (because i<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=921) </p>
		<span class=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D =E2=88=9211 + 23<span c=
lass=3D"large">i</span></span></div>



</div>=20

<p>And this:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: (1 + <span class=3D"large">i</span>)<sup>2</sup></h3>=20

	<div class=3D"two">  <span class=3D"lt"> (1 + <span class=3D"large">i</spa=
n>)(1 + <span class=3D"large">i</span>)</span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D 1=C3=
=971 + 1=C3=97<span class=3D"large">i</span> + 1=C3=97<span class=3D"large"=
>i</span> + <span class=3D"large">i</span><sup>2</sup></span> <span class=
=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D 1 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span> =
=E2=88=92 1 </span>
	=09
		<p>&nbsp; (because i<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=921) </p>
	=09
		<span class=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D 0 + 2<span class=3D"lar=
ge">i</span></span></div>
</div>=20

<h3>But There is a Quicker Way!</h3>=20

<p>Use this rule:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">(a+b<b>i</b>)(c+d<b>i</b>) <em>=
=3D</em> (ac=E2=88=92bd) + (ad+bc)<b>i</b></span></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: (3 + 2<span class=3D"large">i</span>)(1 + 7<span class=3D"larg=
e">i</span>) <em>=3D</em> (3=C3=971 =E2=88=92 2=C3=977) + (3=C3=977 + 2=C3=
=971)<span class=3D"large">i</span> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=9211 + 23<span clas=
s=3D"large">i</span></p>=20
	</div>

<h3>Why Does That Rule Work?</h3>=20

<p>It is just the "FOIL" method after a little work:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two">=20
<div class=3D"lt">Start with:</div>

<div class=3D"rt">(a+b<b>i</b>)(c+d<b>i</b>)</div>

<div class=3D"lt">FOIL method:</div>

<div class=3D"rt">ac + ad<b>i</b> + bc<b>i</b> + bd<b>i</b><sup>2</sup></di=
v>

<div class=3D"lt"><b>i</b><sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=921:</div>

<div class=3D"rt">ac + ad<b>i</b> + bc<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 bd</div>

<div class=3D"lt">Gather like terms:</div>

<div class=3D"rt">(ac =E2=88=92 bd) + (ad + bc)<b>i</b></div>
</div>
<p>And there we have the <span class=3D"large">(ac =E2=88=92 bd) + (ad + bc=
)<b>i</b> </span>  pattern.</p>=20
<p>This rule is certainly faster, but if you forget it, just remember the F=
OIL method.</p>=20

<h3>Let us try <b>i<sup>2</sup></b></h3>=20

<p>Just for fun, let's use the method to calculate<span class=3D"large"> i<=
sup>2</sup></span></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: i<sup>2</sup></h3>=20

	<p>We can write <span class=3D"larger">i</span> with a real and imaginary =
part as <span class=3D"larger">0 + i</span></p>=20
	<div class=3D"two">=20
		 <span class=3D"lt">i<sup>2</sup></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D (0 + i)<s=
up>2</sup></span> <span class=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D (0 + i)=
(0 + i)</span> <span class=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D (0=C3=970 =
=E2=88=92 1=C3=971) + (0=C3=971 + 1=C3=970)<b>i</b></span> <span class=3D"l=
t"></span> <span class=3D"rt">=3D =E2=88=921 + 0<b>i</b></span> <span class=
=3D"lt"></span> <span class=3D"rt"><span class=3D"larger">=3D <b>=E2=88=921=
</b></span></span></div>
</div>=20

<p>And that agrees nicely with the definition that<span class=3D"large"> i<=
sup>2 </sup>=3D =E2=88=921</span></p>=20
<p>So it all works wonderfully!</p>=20
<p>Learn more at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/complex-numb=
er-multiply.html">Complex Number Multiplication</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Conjugates</h2>=20

<p>We will need to use conjugates in a minute!</p>=20
<p>A <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/conjugate.html">conjugat=
e</a> is where we <b>change the sign in the middle</b> like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
omplex-conjugate.svg" alt=3D"Complex Conjugate" height=3D"92" width=3D"264"=
></p>=20
<p>A conjugate can be shown with a little star, or with a bar over it:</p>=
=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><span style=3D"border-top:1px solid;">5 =E2=88=92 3<b>=
i</b></span>   <em>=3D</em>   5 + 3<b>i</b></p>=20
	</div>


<h2>Dividing</h2>=20

<p>The conjugate is used to help complex division.</p>=20
<p>The trick is to <b>multiply both top and bottom</b> by the<b> conjugate =
of the bottom</b>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Do this Division:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>2 + 3<b>i</b></em><st=
rong><span class=3D"larger">4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></span></strong></span></p=
>=20
	<p>Multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of <span class=3D"larger">4 =
=E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></span> :<span class=3D"larger"></span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>2 + 3<b>i</b></em><str=
ong>4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></strong></span>=C3=97<span class=3D"intbl"><em>4 =
+ 5<b>i</b></em><strong>4 + 5<b>i</b></strong></span>  <em>=3D</em>  <span =
class=3D"intbl"><em>8 + 10<b>i</b> + 12<b>i</b> + 15<b>i</b><sup>2</sup></e=
m><strong>16 + 20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 25<b>i</b><sup>2</=
sup></strong></span></p>=20
	<p>Now remember that <span class=3D"larger">i<sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=
=88=921</span>, so:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">=3D  <span class=3D"intbl"><em>8 + 10<b>i</b> + =
12<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 15</em><strong>16 + 20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 20<b>i</b> + =
25</strong></span></p>=20
	<p>Add Like Terms (and notice how on the bottom <span class=3D"larger">20<=
b>i</b> =E2=88=92 20<b>i</b></span> cancels out!):</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">=3D  <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=927 + 22<b=
>i</b></em><strong>41</strong></span></p>=20
	<p>Last we should put the answer back into <span class=3D"larger">a + b<b>=
i</b></span> form:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">=3D  <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=927 </em>=
<strong><span class=3D"larger">41</span></strong></span> + <span class=3D"i=
ntbl"><em>22</em><strong><span class=3D"larger">41</span></strong></span><b=
>i</b></p>=20
	<p>DONE!</p>=20
	</div>
<p>Yes, there is a bit of calculation to do. But it <b>can</b> be done.</p>=
=20


<h2>Multiplying By the Conjugate</h2>=20

<p>There is a faster way though.</p>=20
<p>In the previous example, what happened on the bottom was interesting:</p=
>=20
<p class=3D"center large">(4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b>)(4 + 5<b>i</b>) <em>=3D</e=
m> 16 + 20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 25<b>i</b><sup>2</sup></p=
>=20
<p>The middle terms (20<b>i</b> =E2=88=92 20<b>i</b>) cancel out:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">(4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b>)(4 + 5<b>i</b>) <em>=3D</e=
m> 16 =E2=88=92 25<b>i</b><sup>2</sup></p>=20
<p>Also <span class=3D"larger"><b>i</b><sup>2</sup> <em>=3D</em> =E2=88=921=
</span> :</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">(4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b>)(4 + 5<b>i</b>) <em>=3D</e=
m> 16 + 25</p>=20
<p>And 16 and 25 are (magically) squares of the 4 and 5:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">(4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b>)(4 + 5<b>i</b>) <em>=3D</e=
m> 4<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup></p>=20
<p>Which is really quite a simple result. The general rule is:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">(a + b<b>i</b>)(a =E2=88=92 b<b>=
i</b>) <em>=3D</em> a<sup>2</sup></span><span class=3D"larger"> + b<sup>2</=
sup></span></p>=20
</div>
<p>That can save us time when we do division, like this:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Let's try this again</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>2 + 3<b>i</b></em><st=
rong><span class=3D"larger">4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></span></strong></span></p=
>=20
	<p>Multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of <span class=3D"larger">4 =
=E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></span> :<span class=3D"larger"></span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>2 + 3<b>i</b></em><str=
ong>4 =E2=88=92 5<b>i</b></strong></span> =C3=97 <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=
4 + 5<b>i</b></em><strong>4 + 5<b>i</b></strong></span>  <em>=3D</em>  <spa=
n class=3D"intbl"><em>8 + 10<b>i</b> + 12<b>i</b> + 15<b>i</b><sup>2</sup><=
/em><strong>16 + 25</strong></span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">=3D  <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=927 + 22<b=
>i</b></em><strong>41</strong></span></p>=20
	<p>And then back into <span class=3D"larger">a + b<b>i</b></span> form:</p=
>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">=3D  <span class=3D"intbl"><em>=E2=88=927 </em>=
<strong><span class=3D"larger">41</span></strong></span> + <span class=3D"i=
ntbl"><em>22</em><strong><span class=3D"larger">41</span></strong></span><b=
>i</b></p>=20
	<p>DONE!</p>=20
	</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h2>Notation</h2>=20

<p>We often use <b>z</b> for a complex number. And <b>Re()</b> for the real=
 part and <b>Im()</b> for the imaginary part, like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/c=
omplex-re-im.svg" alt=3D"Complex Number Re() and Im()" height=3D"85" width=
=3D"180"></p>=20
<p>Which looks like this on the complex plane:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/c=
omplex-plane-z-example.svg" alt=3D"complex plane z example" height=3D"187" =
width=3D"236"></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h2>The Mandelbrot Set</h2>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td> <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/mandelbrot-se=
t.jpg" alt=3D"Mandelbrot Set" height=3D"225" width=3D"300"></td>
			<td>=20

<p>The beautiful <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/mandelbrot.h=
tml">Mandelbrot Set</a> (pictured here) is based on Complex Numbers.</p>=20
<p>It is a plot of what happens when we take the simple equation <b>z</b><s=
up>2</sup>+<b>c</b> (both complex numbers) and feed the result back into <b=
>z</b> time and time again.</p>=20
<p>The color shows how fast <b>z</b><sup>2</sup>+<b>c</b> grows, and black =
means it stays within a certain range.</p></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">=20
<p>Here is an image made by zooming into the Mandelbrot set</p></td>
			<td> <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/mandelbroot-z=
oom-a.jpg" alt=3D"Mandelbrot Set Zoomed In" height=3D"224" width=3D"300"></=
td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">And here is the center of the previous o=
ne zoomed in even further:</td>
			<td> <img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/mandelbroot-z=
oom-b.jpg" alt=3D"Mandelbrot Set Zoomed In More" height=3D"224" width=3D"30=
0"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
